The Biofire Respiratory Panel v2.1 assay is a PCR-based assay that enables detection of respiratory pathogens from patient samples. This test was approved by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for testing of nasopharyngeal swabs in viral transport media. This assay was further developed and its performance characteristics have been determined for testing lower respiratory specimens using this method by the Children's Health Dallas Laboratory.
This test detects the presence of nucleic acid and does not assess organism viability. As a result, PCR should not be used as a test of cure. Negative results do not preclude respiratory pathogen infection and should not be used as the sole basis for diagnosis, treatment, or other management decisions.

observation.value:
This is a 4th generation HIV assay that screens for HIV-1 and HIV-2 antibodies and p24 antigen.

For assistance with test interpretation or patient care, an HIV provider is available 24/7: search "ARMS" Clinic through the web directory or ask paging operator for ARMS (AIDS-Related Medical Services) provider on-call.

The Biofire Respiratory Panel v2.1 assay is a PCR-based assay that enables detection of respiratory pathogens from patient samples. This test was approved by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for testing of nasopharyngeal swabs in viral transport media.  This assay was further developed and its performance characteristics have been determined for testing lower respiratory specimens using this method by the Children's Health Dallas Laboratory.

This test detects the presence of nucleic acid and does not assess organism viability. As a result, PCR should not be used as a test of cure. Negative results do not preclude respiratory pathogen infection and should not be used as the sole basis for diagnosis, treatment, or other management decisions.
